          <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>
        </div>

        <div id="kext-allow-button-does-not-work">
          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading">
              <span class="label label-danger pull-right">Trouble</span>
              <h3 class="panel-title"><b>Allow</b> button on <b>System Preferences &gt; Security &amp; Privacy</b> does not work.</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="panel-body">
              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-4">
                  {{#lightbox}}
                    img/system-preferences-security-and-privacy@2x.png An alert of Kext policy
                  {{/lightbox}}
                </div>
              </div>

              <p>
                <b>The allow button</b> on <b>System Preferences &gt; Security &amp; Privacy</b> should be hidden after you click it.<br />
                If the button does not hide after click, you did not succeed to click it.
              </p>

              <p>
                It's because macOS blocks the click if you are using an app which intercepts mouse events.<br />
                You have to quit them before pressing the allow button.
              </p>

              <p>
                <b>Apps which prevent the click:</b>
              </p>

              <ul>
                <li><b>Google Chrome</b></li>
                <li>Dropbox</li>
                <li>MagicPrefs</li>
                <li>SteerMouse</li>
                <li>Witch</li>
                <li>Sonos Desktop Controller for Mac</li>
                <li>If you are using macOS from remote via <b>Screen Sharing</b>, you cannot click the allow button.</li>
                <li>etc.</li>
              </ul>

              <hr class="horizontal-separator thin" />

              <h4>Examine what app prevents the click</h4>

              <p>
                You can examine apps which prevents the click if you are using <b>macOS Mojave or later</b>.
              </p>

              <ol>
                <li>
                  Choose <b>Privacy</b> tab on <b>System Preferences &gt; Security &amp; Privacy</b>.

                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-lg-4">
                      {{#lightbox}}
                        img/system-preferences-security-and-privacy-general@2x.png Privacy tab
                      {{/lightbox}}
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose <b>Accessibility</b>. <br />
                  The enabled apps in the list prevent the click. You have to close these apps.

                  <div class="row">
                    <div class="col-lg-4">
                      {{#lightbox}}
                        img/system-preferences-security-and-privacy-accessibility@2x.png Privacy tab
                      {{/lightbox}}
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <hr class="horizontal-separator thin" />

              <h4>Click Allow button via keyboard operation</h4>

              <p>
                You can press Allow button via keyboard operation if you cannot find such apps that intercept mouse events.
              </p>

              <ol>
                <li>
                  Change Full Keyboard Access configuration.
                  <ol>
                    <li>Open <b>System Preferences &gt; Keyboard &gt; Shortcuts</b>.</li>
                    <li>Change Full Keyboard Access configuration to <b>All controls</b>.</li>
                  </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click Allow button.
                  <ol>
                    <li>Open <b>System Preferences &gt; Security &amp; Privacy</b>.</li>
                    <li>Move focus to Allow button by using <b>tab</b> or <b>shift+tab</b> key.</li>
                    <li>Press <b>spacebar</b> on Allow button.</li>
                  </ol>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <hr class="horizontal-separator thin" />

              <h4>The last resort</h4>

              <p>
                You can press Allow button by starting your Mac in <b>safe mode</b> if you cannot find such apps that intercept mouse events.<br />
                Because any extra apps which prevent clicking the Allow button is not launched automatically in safe mode.
              </p>

              <p>
                The procedure is follows.
              </p>

              <ol>
                <li>Download <a href="./" target="_blank">Karabiner-Elements</a> before restarting your Mac.</li>
                <li>Restart your Mac in safe mode. (<a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT201262" target="_blank">Press and hold the Shift key at boot.</a>)</li>
                <li>Reinstall Karabiner-Elements from downloaded file.</li>
                <li>
                  Open System Preferences and confirm the Allow button is shown.<br />
                  If the Allow button is hidden, close System Preferences and open it again.
                </li>
                <li>Click the Allow button.</li>
                <li>Restart your Mac in normal mode.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

